Note: ========================================
Note: ARM Assembly Lexer
Note: ========================================
Note: Lexer for ARM assembly language (ARMv7/ARMv8 syntax)
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Token Types: Instructions, Registers, Directives, Labels, Numbers, Strings, Symbols
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant TOKEN_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_REGISTER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_LABEL as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_HASH as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_EXCLAIM as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_SHIFT as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0

@Reasoning:
A token is a 4-field heap record so the lexer and parser can share token objects
without copying. We pack into 32 bytes (4 * 8) so allocation aligns to the layout
allocator's slot size and reads avoid unaligned access on ARMv7.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Plain struct: token_type is the TOKEN_* discriminator at offset 0, value is the
byte pointer into the source buffer at offset 8, value_length is the lexeme
length at offset 16, position is the byte offset of the lexeme's start at
offset 24. All fields stay as Integer to permit the field-as-handle pattern.
@End Implementation

Type called "ArmToken":
    token_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    position as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
The lexer carries the source slice, current cursor, and the token output list
together so every scanning helper can operate on a single handle instead of
threading four arguments. Source is held as a pointer (not copied) because the
caller still owns the buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Fields are stored at byte offsets 0, 8, 16, 24 inside a 32-byte allocation.
source is a pointer to the source bytes, source_length is the byte count,
position is the read cursor that advances during tokenization, tokens is a
List handle owning the produced ArmToken objects.
@End Implementation

Type called "ArmLexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    tokens as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructor for ArmLexer. Source length is computed once with string_length so
the scanning loops can compare against a cached value and never re-walk the
source buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte ArmLexer record, writes the source pointer, source length,
the initial position of 0, and a freshly created List handle to receive tokens.
Returns the lexer handle to the caller.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) on the source length because StringCore.string_length walks until NUL.
Cold path: called once per translation unit.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Trusts caller to pass a valid NUL-terminated source pointer. No bounds checks
on the source buffer itself; source ownership remains with the caller. The
returned lexer handle must be released via destroy_lexer to avoid leaking the
underlying List.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new lexer for ARM assembly source

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0
    Let tokens be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, tokens
    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lexer owns its token list but not the source; destroy_lexer must therefore
release the list before freeing the lexer record itself, otherwise the List
handle is leaked.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the token list pointer from offset 24, calls List.destroy on it, then
deallocates the 32-byte lexer record. Source buffer is intentionally left for
the caller to free.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Frees memory that the lexer owns and must not be called twice on the same
handle. After this call, every ArmToken pointer previously pushed into the
list is also invalid (tokens are owned by the list).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_lexer" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Free lexer and token list

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc destroy from List with tokens
    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drives lexical analysis to completion by repeatedly skipping inter-token
whitespace, fetching one token, and appending it to the lexer's list. Stops
on a NUL token (next_token's EOF sentinel) or on a token with token_type 0,
matching create_token's failure encoding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infinite While guarded by two exit conditions: token equal to 0 (allocation
failure) and token_type equal to 0 (EOF). Whitespace skipping preserves
newlines because ARM line structure (one instruction per line) is significant.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) over the source where n is the byte length. Each iteration does at most
constant scanning work plus one List append. Hot path during translation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes attacker-supplied source. Relies on next_token and skip_whitespace
to keep the cursor within source_length. Side effect: appends to the lexer's
token list.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "tokenize" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Main tokenization loop

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace_not_newline from lexer
        Let token be proc next_token from lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc push from List with tokens, token
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM assembly is line-oriented (one instruction per line), so newlines are
significant tokens; this helper exists to skip only horizontal whitespace and
comments while leaving '\n' for next_token to emit as TOKEN_NEWLINE. Recognises
both ';' (GAS) and '@' (ARM ADS) line-comment markers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/source/source_length from the lexer, then walks bytes: 0x20
(space) and 0x09 (tab) advance the cursor by 1; 0x3B (';') and 0x40 ('@')
delegate to skip_comment which advances to end-of-line; any other byte stops
the loop and writes the current cursor back to lexer offset 16.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) where k is the number of consecutive whitespace/comment bytes. Tight
inner loop; called once per token request.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "skip_whitespace_not_newline" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip spaces and tabs but preserve newlines for ARM assembly structure

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If char is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 59:  Note: ; (comment)
                    proc skip_comment from lexer
                    Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                Otherwise:
                    If char is equal to 64:  Note: @ (comment in ARM)
                        proc skip_comment from lexer
                        Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                    Otherwise:
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                        Return
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comments in ARM assembly run to end-of-line. Pulled out of
skip_whitespace_not_newline so both ';' and '@' comment-start markers can
share one implementation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks bytes from the lexer cursor until it hits 0x0A ('\n'); the newline is
intentionally left for next_token so line boundaries remain visible. Writes
the final cursor back to offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip comment until end of line

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Central dispatcher producing one ArmToken per call. Implements ARM-specific
one-byte tokens directly (newline, comma, brackets, braces, '#', '!', ':')
and dispatches longer tokens (strings, directives, numbers, identifiers) to
specialised helpers. Assumes skip_whitespace_not_newline has positioned the
cursor at the start of a real token or at EOF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an EOF token (token_type 0) when position is at or past source_length.
Otherwise inspects the byte at the cursor and routes: 0x0A -> NEWLINE,
0x2C -> COMMA, 0x5B/5D -> LBRACKET/RBRACKET, 0x7B/7D -> LBRACE/RBRACE,
0x23 -> HASH (immediate prefix), 0x21 -> EXCLAIM (writeback indicator),
0x3A -> COLON (label terminator), 0x22 -> lex_string, 0x2E -> lex_directive,
ASCII digit or '-' -> lex_number, alphabetic -> lex_identifier. Unknown bytes
advance the cursor and recurse.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) per token excluding the dispatched helpers. Hot path: called once per
token in tokenize.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes attacker-controlled source. The recursive case for unknown bytes is
bounded because the cursor advances by 1 before recursing, so recursion depth
is at most the number of unknown bytes between two real tokens; this is finite
but stack-noisy on adversarial input, which the parser layer rate-limits.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return proc create_token with 0, 0, 0, position
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Note: Check for newline
    If char is equal to 10:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for comma
    If char is equal to 44:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for brackets (memory addressing)
    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for braces (register lists)
    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for hash (immediate value prefix in ARM)
    If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HASH, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for exclamation (writeback indicator)
    If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EXCLAIM, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for colon (label definition)
    If char is equal to 58:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for string literal
    If char is equal to 34:
        Return proc lex_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for directive (starts with .)
    If char is equal to 46:
        Return proc lex_directive from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for number (including negative)
    Let is_digit be 0
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Set is_digit to 1
        End If
    End If

    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_number from lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:  Note: Minus sign
        Return proc lex_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier (instruction, register, label)
    Let is_alpha be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Unknown character - skip it
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
    Return proc next_token from lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Strings appear in ARM assembly only in directive operands (e.g. .ascii "hi").
We scan past the opening quote and consume bytes until the matching close
quote, honouring '\' as a one-byte escape so escaped quotes don't terminate
the literal early.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos, steps past the opening 0x22, then walks bytes: 0x22 closes
the literal and advances past it; 0x5C (backslash) consumes two bytes
(escape sequence); any other byte consumes one. Produces a TOKEN_STRING whose
value pointer is source+start_pos and length covers both quotes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L) where L is literal length. Single linear pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted input. Unterminated strings are bounded by source_length (the loop
condition); the token will simply extend to EOF rather than over-read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 34:  Note: Closing quote
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set position to position plus 2
        Otherwise:
            Set position to position plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM (GAS-style) directives are an introducer '.' followed by alphanumeric
characters (.text, .global, .word, .ascii). Recognising them as a single
token keeps directive parsing cheap.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_pos at the '.', skips past it, then consumes the contiguous
run of alphanumeric bytes via is_alnum. Emits TOKEN_DIRECTIVE whose lexeme
includes the leading dot so downstream code can dispatch by full directive
name.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L) in the directive name length. Each iteration calls is_alnum.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "lex_directive" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex assembler directive (starts with .)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alnum from char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DIRECTIVE, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM immediates appear as plain decimal, signed decimal ('-1'), or hex ('0x1F').
Decoding only validates the lexeme; numeric conversion is deferred to the
parser so the lexer stays one-pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures start_pos. If the first byte is '-' (0x2D), advances one byte to
absorb the sign. Then peeks two bytes for a "0x" hex prefix; if present,
consumes the prefix and the trailing run of hex digits (is_hex_digit).
Otherwise consumes a run of ASCII decimal digits (0x30..0x39). Emits
TOKEN_NUMBER with the full lexeme.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L) over the digit run. Hot path on numeric-heavy assembly.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex number (decimal, hex, octal, binary)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Handle negative sign
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
    If char is equal to 45:
        Set position to position plus 1
    End If

    Note: Check for hex prefix (0x)
    If position is less than source_length minus 1:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
        If c1 is equal to 48:
            If c2 is equal to 120:  Note: 0x
                Set position to position plus 2
                Note: Lex hex digits
                While position is less than source_length:
                    Let hex_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
                    Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit from hex_char
                    If is_hex is not equal to 1:
                        Break
                    End If
                    Set position to position plus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                Let length be position minus start_pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Lex decimal digits
    While position is less than source_length:
        Let digit_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_digit be 0
        If digit_char is greater than or equal to 48:
            If digit_char is less than or equal to 57:
                Set is_digit to 1
            End If
        End If
        If is_digit is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Set length to position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifiers are the dominant token class in assembly (instructions, registers,
shift names, labels, and user symbols). One scan extracts the lexeme; a
follow-up classify_token call assigns the final TOKEN_* discriminator so the
parser can switch on it directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads bytes while is_alnum returns 1 or the byte equals 0x5F (underscore).
The terminating byte is left for next_token. The lexeme is handed to
classify_token, which returns TOKEN_INSTRUCTION, TOKEN_REGISTER, TOKEN_SHIFT,
or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L) over identifier length followed by an O(table) classify_token call. Hot
path.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "lex_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex identifier (instruction, register, label, or symbol)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alnum from char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            If char is not equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                Break
            End If
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos

    Note: Classify as instruction, register, or identifier
    Let token_type be proc classify_token with source plus start_pos, length
    Return proc create_token with token_type, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
After lex_identifier captures a lexeme we still need to decide whether it is
a register (r0..r15, sp, lr, pc, fp), an ARMv7 mnemonic (mov, add, ldr, str,
bl, bx, etc.), a shift name (LSL, LSR, ASR, ROR), or just a label/symbol.
We branch first on lexeme length so the longer mnemonic comparisons only run
when the length matches.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads bytes via memory_get_byte and uses match_string to compare against a
hand-coded list of register/shift/instruction names organised by length. The
register check for r0..r15 special-cases the 'r' prefix and verifies the
trailing byte is an ASCII digit. Returns TOKEN_INSTRUCTION, TOKEN_REGISTER,
TOKEN_SHIFT, or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (fallthrough).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(M) where M is the number of mnemonic comparisons at the matching length
band (at most a few dozen). Each match_string is O(L).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "classify_token" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify identifier as instruction, register, shift, or generic identifier

    Note: Check for registers (r0-r15, sp, lr, pc, fp)
    If length is equal to 2:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        If c1 is equal to 114:  Note: r
            Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
            If c2 is greater than or equal to 48:
                If c2 is less than or equal to 57:
                    Return TOKEN_REGISTER
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Let is_sp be proc match_string with text, "sp", 2
        If is_sp is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REGISTER
        End If

        Let is_lr be proc match_string with text, "lr", 2
        If is_lr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REGISTER
        End If

        Let is_pc be proc match_string with text, "pc", 2
        If is_pc is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REGISTER
        End If

        Let is_fp be proc match_string with text, "fp", 2
        If is_fp is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REGISTER
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 3:
        Note: Check for r10-r15
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        If c1 is equal to 114:  Note: r
            If c2 is equal to 49:  Note: r1x
                Return TOKEN_REGISTER
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check common ARM instructions
        Let is_mov be proc match_string with text, "mov", 3
        If is_mov is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_add be proc match_string with text, "add", 3
        If is_add is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_sub be proc match_string with text, "sub", 3
        If is_sub is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_mul be proc match_string with text, "mul", 3
        If is_mul is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_cmp be proc match_string with text, "cmp", 3
        If is_cmp is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_and be proc match_string with text, "and", 3
        If is_and is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_orr be proc match_string with text, "orr", 3
        If is_orr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_eor be proc match_string with text, "eor", 3
        If is_eor is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_ldr be proc match_string with text, "ldr", 3
        If is_ldr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_str be proc match_string with text, "str", 3
        If is_str is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Note: Check shift operators
        Let is_lsl be proc match_string with text, "lsl", 3
        If is_lsl is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SHIFT
        End If

        Let is_lsr be proc match_string with text, "lsr", 3
        If is_lsr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SHIFT
        End If

        Let is_asr be proc match_string with text, "asr", 3
        If is_asr is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SHIFT
        End If

        Let is_ror be proc match_string with text, "ror", 3
        If is_ror is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SHIFT
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Let is_push be proc match_string with text, "push", 4
        If is_push is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_pop be proc match_string with text, "pop", 4
        If is_pop is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_movw be proc match_string with text, "movw", 4
        If is_movw is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_movt be proc match_string with text, "movt", 4
        If is_movt is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_ldrb be proc match_string with text, "ldrb", 4
        If is_ldrb is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_strb be proc match_string with text, "strb", 4
        If is_strb is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_ldrh be proc match_string with text, "ldrh", 4
        If is_ldrh is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_strh be proc match_string with text, "strh", 4
        If is_strh is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 1:
        Let is_b be proc match_string with text, "b", 1
        If is_b is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 2:
        Let is_bl be proc match_string with text, "bl", 2
        If is_bl is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If

        Let is_bx be proc match_string with text, "bx", 2
        If is_bx is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    Note: Not a recognized instruction or register, treat as identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hand-rolled isalpha to keep the lexer self-contained (no libc) and to match
ASCII semantics precisely. Avoiding the C runtime keeps the bootstrap chain
deterministic across hosts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if the byte is in [0x61..0x7A] (a..z) or [0x41..0x5A] (A..Z),
otherwise 0. No locale handling - assembly is strictly ASCII.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Used while scanning identifiers and directives. Built on is_alpha so the
alphabetic case is shared and a single source of truth governs ASCII class
membership.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to is_alpha for the alphabetic case. Otherwise returns 1 for ASCII
digits 0x30..0x39, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha_char be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha_char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Used specifically by lex_number to consume the body of a 0x... hex literal.
Accepts both upper- and lower-case hex letters per ARM/GAS conventions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for 0x30..0x39 (0..9), 0x61..0x66 (a..f), or 0x41..0x46 (A..F),
else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hex digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
classify_token compares many candidate mnemonics against the captured lexeme
without copying or NUL-terminating it. This helper does a byte-wise compare
of exactly 'length' bytes so we can match against a literal Runa String
without allocating a copy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear byte-by-byte compare via memory_get_byte for both sides. Returns 0 at
the first mismatch, 1 if all length bytes match.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(length). Called many times during classify_token.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "match_string" takes text as Integer, target as String, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare string with target

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with target, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allocates an ArmToken record matching the type's 32-byte layout. Centralising
the layout writes here means changes to the ArmToken shape only need to be
made in two places (this constructor and the type definition).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes via Layout.allocate, writes token_type at offset 0,
value_ptr at offset 8, value_length at offset 16, and position at offset 24.
Returns the token pointer for the lexer to push into its token list.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, value_ptr as Integer, value_length as Integer, position as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new token

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, value_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, position
    Return token
End Process
